04278nam a22006855i 9780271065717DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710657177 a10.1515/97802710657172doi  a(DE-B1597)584358  a(OCoLC)1253313797  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0130002bisacsh04a811/.42231 aGilpin, W. Clark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligion Around Emily Dickinson /cW. Clark Gilpin. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion Around ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Reshaping a Religious Repertoire -- t2. Society and Solitude -- t3. Domesticity and the Divine -- t4. An Intimate Absence -- t5. The Cadences of Time -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tIndex of Poems0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion Around Emily Dickinson begins with a seeming paradox posed by Dickinson's posthumously published works: while her poems and letters contain many explicitly religious themes and concepts, throughout her life she resisted joining her local church and rarely attended services. Prompted by this paradox, W. Clark Gilpin proposes, first, that understanding the religious aspect of the surrounding culture enhances our appreciation of Emily Dickinson's poetry and, second, that her poetry casts light on features of religion in nineteenth-century America that might otherwise escape our attention. Religion, especially Protestant Christianity, was "around" Emily Dickinson not only in explicitly religious practices, literature, architecture, and ideas but also as an embedded influence on normative patterns of social organization in the era, including gender roles, education, and ideals of personal intimacy and fulfillment. Through her poetry, Dickinson imaginatively reshaped this richly textured religious inheritance to create her own personal perspective on what it might mean to be religious in the nineteenth century. The artistry of her poetry and the profundity of her thought have meant that this personal perspective proved to be far more than "merely" personal. Instead, Dickinson's creative engagement with the religion around her has stimulated and challenged successive generations of readers in the United States and around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPoetryxReligious aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aProtestantism and literature. 0aProtestantismzNew EnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aReligious poetry, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Literature & the Arts.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271065717?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271065717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271065717/original  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK